<div id="body">
    
    <h2>@appName</h2>

    <p>
        My first experiments with the Microsoft Garage's <a href="https://www.epiloglaser.com/products/legend-laser-series.htm">Epilog Helix</a> 
        laser cutter were artistic 3D models, using <a href="http://www.123dapp.com/make">Autodesk 123D Make</a>.
    </p>
    <h3>Design Process</h3>
    <p>
        The Epilog laser cutter will laser cut / raster engrave anything that can be printed to it using a custom printer driver. 
        The general process is to design the laser cut sequence and print to PDF, with thin (sub-pixel) lines for cuts. Anything too large will be raster-engraved.
    </p>
    <p>
        For engineering designs, I start with <a href="http://products.office.com/en-us/visio/flowchart-software">Visio</a> to generate the initial PDF, 
        while for the artistic designs 123D Make generated the initial PDF. Once I had the initial PDF, I would pass it through 
        <a href="https://inkscape.org/en/">Inkscape</a>  to clean up the design, ensure all the lines were thin enough, and compress the pieces to save on 
        plastic used in the laser cutter.
    </p>
    <div class="content-wrapper">
        <article>
            <img class="imgScaler" src="~/Content/Projects/Models/laser_plans.png" />
            <br />
            <img class="imgScaler" src="~/Content/Projects/Models/space_shuttle.jpg" />
            <br />
            <img class="imgScaler" src="~/Content/Projects/Models/plastic_holder1.jpg" />
        </article>
        <projectAside>
            <h4>Example</h4>
            <p>
                First: The laser-cut traceout for the Space Shuttle model, combined with a test design for a 3D printer plastic holder.
            </p>
            <p>
                Second: Space Shuttle model, after cutout and assembly.
            </p>
            <p>
                Third: Testing of the 3D printer plastic holder.
                <br />
                <i>Unfortunately, due to the positioning of the Printerbot plastic feed input, friction in the holder, and lack 
                   of stability in the holder, I was not able to use the 3D printer plastic holder.
                </i>
            </p>
        </projectAside>
    </div>
    <p>
        When in Inkscape, you must also ensure to:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Remove the laser cut border (or it will be laser cut)</li>
        <li>Remove extraneous text (or it will be rastered)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        After performing your updates in Inkscape, you can print from there or export from PDF and print that file instead.
    </p>
